<font color="#FF0000">THANK YOU, HUMMING EAGLE</font><br>
<tt>Fri Aug  1 20:33:56 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Humming Eagle,<br><br>
I have a friend who has been following this thread. We spoke last night. He told me that he holds Lakota Wisdom in the highest esteem. In my mind, your lesson of the Black Wolf and the White Wolf, shows me why my friend holds such a high opinion.<br><br>
There are many things of value in the lesson, aside from my challenge of finding enough food for my White Wolf! White Wolf, Black Wolf, pairs of opposites, the eternal struggle in us all. I am aware that my Black Wolf will never go away. By feeding my White Wolf, I can keep my Black Wolf very preoccupied, however. A profound but very practical way to approach an eternal core problem. Tunkasila are wise ones, indeed. I will not ask why I have wolves in the first place! <br><br>
The lesson also teaches me that it is through the action of the individual that these conflicts are tamed. This honors the individual by giving the individual mastery over his own fate. Survival and honor depend on correct individual action.<br><br>
I will hold the image of the Black Wolf and the White Wolf in my mind, and begin to focus on my White Wolf. As I said, White Wolf food is scarce sometimes, and that is a shortage upon which I must work. As I go back in time, and over many of the historical posts on this site, I think perhaps it was White Wolf food for which I have been looking, but did not really know it at the time! <br><br>
Thanks!
<p><code>--   (Arthur Varanelli) </code><p>


